/-- **`n`-dimensional `‚Ą§`-lattice Poisson summation ‚ÄĒ the theta
transformation law** (PROVEN 2026-07-24, in
`Fermat.FLT.GaloisRepresentation.HardlyRamified.ZLatticePoisson` ‚ÄĒ
this was THE genuinely new analytic mathematics of the Dedekind
continuation, the gap named in the decomposition of
`completedClassZeta_exists`): for a full-rank `‚Ą§`-lattice `L` in a
finite-dimensional real inner product space `E` (carrying its
canonical Lebesgue measure, `measureSpaceOfInnerProductSpace`) and
every `t > 0`,

`őł_L(1/t) = covol(L)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ ¬∑ t^{n/2} ¬∑ őł_{L‚ą®}(t)`,

where `őł_M(u) := ő£_{v ‚ąą M} exp(‚ąíŌÄ¬∑u¬∑‚ÄĖv‚ÄĖ¬≤)`, `n = dim_‚ĄĚ E`, and
`L‚ą® = {x | ‚ąÄ v ‚ąą L, ‚ü™x, v‚üę ‚ąą ‚Ą§}` is the dual lattice
(`LinearMap.BilinForm.dualSubmodule (inner‚āó E) L`).  This is Poisson
summation `ő£_{v ‚ąą L} f(v) = covol(L)‚ĀĽ¬Ļ ¬∑ ő£_{w ‚ąą L‚ą®} fŐā(w)` at the
Gaussian `f = exp(‚ąíŌÄ‚ÄĖ¬∑‚ÄĖ¬≤/t)` ‚ÄĒ Neukirch, *Algebraic Number Theory*,
VII (3.6) at the scalar modulus; the anisotropic law Neukirch actually
integrates over the unit domain follows from this scalar statement
applied to diagonally rescaled lattices (see
`heckeClassZeta_of_zlattice_theta`).  Note the statement is also true
